<HEADLINE> Roundup: Britain Urged to Be More Cooperative on HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese side on the
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG) today urged the British
side to change their attitude and to be more cooperative on
related issues that have not been solved.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the three-day 40th plenary session
of the JLG which ended here today, Ambassador Zhao Jihua, Chinese
senior representative on the JLG, said that the Chinese side felt
very disappointed at the failure of the British side to adopt a
positive and cooperative approach at the session.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is still much work to do for the JLG in the
remaining days before the handover, such as the transfer of Hong
Kong government assets and Hong Kong archives and some other
issues on which no progress was made at this just concluded
plenary session.
</P>
<P>
"The British side should be more cooperative and have
consultations with the Chinese side on these matters, so as to
find earliest possible solutions to all these issues well before
July 1," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past 12 years the JLG has basically solved
most of the subjects that have been discussed by the two sides
within the framework of the JLG.
</P>
<P>
"I should say the discussion and settlement of these issues
have helped to ensure a smooth transition and helped to ensure the
long-term stability and prosperity of Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it has been proven that it is quite necessary to set
up the Sino-British JLG and to have consultations in the JLG for
the smooth transition and for the long-term stability and
prosperity of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"With the great efforts we have made over the past years, we
have laid a solid foundation for Hong Kong to continue to be an
international financial, shipping and trade center," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have so far discussed and had
consultations on many economic matters which straddle July 1,
1997, and with the appointment of the SAR Chief Executive and
principal SAR government officials, all these economic issues have
been gradually transferred to the SAR government, because these
economic issues are within the scope of the high-degree autonomy
of the HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
"We did make it very clear to the British side that in the
final days before the handover, if the British side takes any
major measure on economic matters that straddle July 1, 1997, we
have a responsibility to express our concern and we have asked the
British side to have consultations with us," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the handover ceremony, he said that so far the
two sides have laid down a basic arrangement for related issues in
general.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the British side to take effective measures to
resolve the question of Vietnamese boat people and refugees.
</P>
<P>
Britain should take the lead in accepting and resettling
Vietnamese refugees held up in Hong Kong and not leave a burden on
the future HKSAR government, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated that the sole role that the JLG plays is
"liaison", not "monitoring", both before and after July 1, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
