<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Report on Intelligence Head's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Israel denied today a newspaper
report which quoted army intelligence head Moshe Yaalon as
saying that Egypt needed a psychiatrist to sort out its
contradictory policy toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
The leading Hebrew daily Yediot Ahronot reported that Yaalon
was quoted by diplomatic sources as making the satiric remarks
on Egypt. At today's weekly Cabinet meeting, Yaalon strongly
denied having made such comments.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also denied at the meeting
that Yaalon had ever made such statements, adding the report was
false and should be viewed with great severity.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai stressed that the report has caused unnecessary
damage both to the army intelligence head, whose assessments are
usually highly regarded, and to the sensitive relations with
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Today's report was published in the wake of a summit held
Tuesday in Sharm el-Sheikh by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. The two leaders
discussed ways of reviving the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The summit was seen as a change of attitude by both Israel and
Egypt, which had been at odds with each other over the current
deadlock in the peace process. Before the summit, Egypt used to
join the Palestinians' verbal attacks against Israel for
sabotaging the peace process, while Israel blamed Cairo for
being an obstacle to advancing peace.
</P>
<P>
Following the summit, Mubarak promised to take upon the role
of mediator between Israel and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) in order to break the deadlock in the peace process. He is
working to arrange a three-way summit, which will include PNA
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
In his first shuttle mission, Mubarak's special envoy Osama
Baz traveled to Gaza Wednesday to brief Arafat on the results of
the Sharm el-Sheik summit. Baz then visited Tel Aviv Thursday to
brief Netanyahu on his meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources said Baz is expected to return back in the
coming days for another shuttle mission aimed at breaking the
Israeli-Palestinian deadlock since Israel began building the Har
Homa settlement in East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
