<HEADLINE> Game to Spread Patriotism among Computer Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 30 (Xinhua) -- A computer software game on the
Opium War (1840-1842), developed by the Optical Memory National
Engineering Research Center of Qinghua University, will be issued
15 days before Hong Kong's return to the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The game, which took one year to produce and cost approximately
one million yuan (120,000 US dollars), is a multi-media creation
featuring the large-scale anti-intrusion battle that occurred in
modern Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The developers hope that the game will help to educate computer
fans about Hong Kong's history of takeover by imperialist powers,
and help them to learn more about the patriotic spirit of those
who laid down their lives for the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The game is the first of its kind ever developed in China.
</P>
<P>
Students from the Beijing No. 4 Middle School who have
experimented with the software called it "a really fascinating and
inspiring game." 
</P>
</TEXT>
