<HEADLINE> China to Increase Investment for Scientific Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 30 (Xinhua) -- China is to strengthen its
scientific research conditions including lab animals, chemical
reagents, books, and information networks by offering more
government funds and bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan, Vice Minister of the State Science and Technology
Commission said today at the closing session of a national
conference on science conditions that by the year 2000, China will
spend two billion yuan (nearly 250 million US dollars) to
build a number of advanced scientific installations.
</P>
<P>
The installations include an advanced sky survey telescope, a
national synchronous radiation laboratory, and an earth crust
monitoring network.
</P>
<P>
Deng added that China listed "the development of scientific
facilities and lab conditions" in the state plan to tackle key
scientific research problems, from which the project can receive
state funds.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan said China is to put 14.2 percent more money on
scientific development compared to last year. Banks will also
offer nearly 20 billion yuan (2.5 billion dollars) in loans to
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
She said China will focus its support on projects concerning
basic research and scientific bases and the establishment of state
lab animal breeding centers, data banks of plant seeds, and
informations networks.
</P>
<P>
China is also to speed up the building of the networks of
supply and maintenance of scientific facilities, the upgrading of
the present equipment, and to call for the joint purchasing and
use of expensive scientific facilities by research institutes.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan said, China will enhance its development of scientific
resources by seeking government and corporate funds as well as
financial support from other social organizations.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investments and donations from international
organizations are also welcome for some of the projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
