<HEADLINE> Taliban Militia Flushed Out of Key Northern Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Anti-Taliban forces led by
commander Ahmad Shah Masood today seized Jabul Siraj, the key
northern town located about 77 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today from Kabul said that the Taliban
have also withdrawn their forces from three northern provinces of
Jozjan, Sar-i-Pol and Faryab.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban entered the three northern provinces only last week
after general Abdul Malik, a key commander under Uzbek warlord
Abdul Rashid Dostam, rebelled.
</P>
<P>
After overrunning Jabul Siraj, Masood forces are now heading
towards Charikar. The Taliban and Masood forces are locked in
heavy fighting for control of Charikar, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Charikar, capital of northern Parwan province, lies about 65
kilometers from Kabul near the strategic Salang Highway leading to
the north.
</P>
<P>
Taliban officials had conceded the fall of Jabul Siraj.
However, they called it a "tactical withdrawal", one report said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban forces suffered heavy casualties Thursday when Massood
launched a pre-dawn attack and captured Gulbahar and Sherqat, two
strategic towns at the mouth of the Panjshir valley, where his
troops are located.  
</P>
</TEXT>
