<HEADLINE> Fighting Rages in Afghan Northern Provincial Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting was continuing
between Afghan Islamic Taliban militia around Charikar, a major
city north of Kabul, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who suffered a series of setbacks over the past
few days, were struggling to defend Charikar, capital of northern
Parwan province, after losing a nearby town of Jabul Siraj,
reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have confirmed the fall of Jabul Siraj, 77
kilometers from the Afghan capital, to forces loyal to Ahmad
Masood, former military chief of the ousted Afghan government, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ousted Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani, has
reportedly returned to a base controlled by Masood in Afghanistan
today. Masood is now heading the anti-Taliban forces waging
counter offensives against the student militia.
</P>
<P>
Masood's forces have seized the key northern town of Jabul
Siraj from the Islamic militia as well as three vital provinces,
dealing a second blow to the Taliban in less than a week.
