<HEADLINE> UNICEF Seeks Africa's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) is seeking the support of African countries on its call for
an international ban on child labour, recruitment of children into
military forces and the production, storage and use in landmines.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Deputy Director Stephen Lewis said here today that his
organisation was concerned that children continued to bear the brunt
of economic and social upheavals and armed conflicts in africa.
</P>
<P>
He said his organisation was attending the Organisation of African
Unity's Council of Ministers and heads of state and government
meetings in Harare to drum up support for its anti-landmine and
anti-child labour stance.
</P>
<P>
Between 80 and 100 million children were involved in child labour
of one form or the other or were exposed to hazardous conditions in
Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of initiatives, he said, had been mooted in conjunction
with the OAU, governmental and non-governmental organisations which
might ensure a hopeful future for African children.
</P>
<P>
He said in its effort to stop the violation of children's rights
UNICEF was calling for the immediate elimination of hazardous child
labour, the legal protection of children, the production of data on
child labour and the signing of an international protocal on the ban
of child labour and landmines. enditem

