<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Economy Continues Uptrend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine economy continued to
be robust during the first quarter this year, with a stable strong
growth in the gross national product (GNP), a downtrend in
inflation and a rallying stock market.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, the GNP, buoyed by strong showing of
agriculture and services sectors, grew by 6.1 percent, slightly
lower than the expected 6.4 percent and the revised year-ago level
of 6.9 percent, according to official figures released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP), on the other hand, rose by 5
percent, close to the year-ago level of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The GNP is a country's total output of goods and services,
including income from abroad such as remittances of overseas
contract workers, while the GDP refers to the figure after
adjustment for foreign income.
</P>
<P>
Despite a slowdown in the GNP, both government economic
managers and many private analysts here agreed that the country's
economy progressed at a comfortably healthy pace, contrary to
initial negative market expectations.
</P>
<P>
The stock market and the country's currency peso have both come
under strong pressure since late April, largely on fears that the
Philippines' economy was on a serious downturn and would soon
suffer the same fate as Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that the country's growth for the rest of
the year is expected to accelerate and thus the government's
average growth rate target of 7 to 8 percent for the full year
will still be attained.
</P>
<P>
The actual economic growth rates for the first quarter,
although slightly weaker compared to year-ago levels, were just
within or little less than expectations, they explained.
</P>
<P>
They said the poor showing in industry sector led by
manufacturing, a key factor blamed for the slowdown of the entire
economy, was temporary.
</P>
<P>
From January to March, industrial output grew only 3.8 percent,
compared to 6.1 percent a year earlier, due to restructuring in
manufacturing and labor-related problems in rubber, textile and
metal industries.
</P>
<P>
"A pick-up in growth is expected to materialize in the next
quarters as economic restructuring continues and certain troubled
sectors get out of their temporary difficulties," said Planning
Secretary Celieto Habito.
</P>
<P>
Another vital economic indicator, the average inflation rate
for the first quarter, settled at 4.7 percent, a sharp decrease
from last year's 8.4 percent. Inflation for April dipped further
to 4.6 percent from 4.8 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by this trend, the government Wednesday scaled down
its inflation targets for 1997 and 1998 to show confidence in the
economy and dispel fears that the country could go the way of
Thailand, which has experienced a bumpy economic growth and
currency troubles in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The target for 1997 was reduced to 5.2 to 5.7 percent from 6 to
6.5 percent, while that for 1998 was lowered from 6 to 5.5 percent
even in view of the national elections that year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's stock market has begun to regain some
of its lost grounds in recent weeks after the Central Bank took a
series of measures to prevent speculative attacks on peso and
limit banks' exposure to the property sector.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stocks index (Phisix) reached an all-time high
of 3,447.60 points on February 3 but began to dump since late
April because of fears of a glut of property and a destabilized
economy.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank reduced again the overnight borrowing and
lending rates to 16 percent and 18 percent, respectively, Thursday
as the stock market continued to rebound for six consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
One day after the announcement of the first quarter
macro-economic fundamentals, the Phisix jumped by 50.84 points
today to 2,809.45 points.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to stabilize as investors' confidence in
the economy further improved after they gained a clearer picture
of the country's overall economic situation, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
