<HEADLINE> Susanti Signs Off With Smiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's badminton
queen Susi Susanti signed off her last world badminton champions
here on Friday but said she would still play one year.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to play maybe one more year and I have duty to
bring youngsters up for Indonesia's women's singles," said Susanti
after her straight-game loss to China's Gong Zhichao in the
quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
But she then said even one year was not guaranteed because she
would have to consult her husband Allan Budi Kusuma.
</P>
<P>
"I have to discuss this with Allan," she said. "It Allan
said 'Stop' I would stop (playing)."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Chinese dominance in the event, Susanti said the
Chinese still have players like South Korea's Ra Kyung Min and her
compatriot Mia Audina to look out.
</P>
<P>
Susanti sung praise for her opponent Gong, saying "She has
potentials and she would follow my steps to the titles."
</P>
<P>
Susanti, who married Allan Budi Kusuma this February, is one of
the all-time giant in the sport.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old has had all major titles under her belt,
including the world championships, all England, world cup, the
Olympics and world grand prix. 
</P>
