<HEADLINE> Britain Hopes for Revival of Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett said here today that the only
way to achieve the peace in the region is to sign an agreement of
just and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett made the remark upon departure today after winding up
the first fact-finding tour in the region of a minister in the
newly-elected British Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut International Airport, the
British official stressed that expectations for progress in the
Middle East peace process have not totally died.
</P>
<P>
"We should work for a revival of the peace process and
find out the means to resume the peace negotiations," Fatchett
said.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to achieve the peace in the region is to sign an
agreement of just and comprehensive peace because it is in the
interests of all sides and will realize stability, security and
economic prosperity," he added.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the necessity for all the parties involved in the
peace process to have confidence in others and in themselves.
</P>
<P>
"We should work in order to reach conditions to ensure the
achievement of progress in the peace talks, and what I felt
from my meetings with the leaders in the region is that we
should not give up the peace process, but should seriously
treat the issue," Fatchett said.
</P>
<P>
The British minister began his tour earlier in the week
with a visit to Egypt, followed by Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas of West Bank and Gaza Strip, Jordan and Syria.
</P>
<P>
During his short stay in Beirut, he held meetings with
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and
Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
