<HEADLINE> SIB's Campaign on Review into Pensions Misselling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Investments Board
(SIB) launched today an advertising campaign designed to heighten
the public's awareness of the review into pensions misselling.
</P>
<P>
The campaign forms part of the investor awareness program,
which will also target selected trade and consumer publications
and other suitable media.
</P>
<P>
Under the banner, "Have You Lost Out On Your Pension?", the
advertisements seek to underline the importance of the public
playing its part in the review.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the publicity program has been chosen to coincide
with the mailing of questionnaires by firms to investors.
</P>
<P>
It is vital that investors respond to the questionnaire, even
if they are unable to provide all the information asked for, the
SIB said. Otherwise, their case cannot be resolved speedily.
</P>
<P>
For the next three months, investors can call a 24 hour
freephone for a free copy of the SIB factsheet on the review.
</P>
<P>
The advertisements convey the purpose of the review and how it
works in a way that is clear, eye-catching, and informative.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that two out of five people contacted by firms
which sold them a personal pension do not reply to letters asking
for information about whether they might have been missold a
personal pension.
</P>
<P>
Unless investors reply, they may miss out on their right to
redress. By the end of March 1997 investors had accepted offers of
redress worth a total of 163.477 million US dollars to 12,650
people, an average of 12,000 US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
