<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRI Forecasts World Car Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- By 2002, global automotive capacity
will increase by 11 million units, according to a forecast by
DRI/McGraw-Hill.
</P>
<P>
With auto manufacturers racing to seize emerging market
opportunities, these markets will account for 86 percent of the
capacity expansion, said the report due to be published early
next month.
</P>
<P>
Developing Asia alone will absorb 54 percent of the growth
increasing capacity by 5.8 million units, while Eastern Europe and
South America will account for 3.2 million units or 32 percent of
the increase.
</P>
<P>
"Strategic considerations, not over capacity issues, dominate
emerging markets as auto manufacturers continue to announce new
assembly activity," noted Philippe Schwarz, managing director,
DRI/McGraw-Hill Global Automotive Services.
</P>
<P>
"However, with more and more manufacturers entering these
markets and increasing competition, the utilization rates fall.
This is a clear threat to large investments," he added.
</P>
<P>
The forecast said that the global capacity utilization rates
will remain at around 76 percent, well below the optimal rate of
90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Developing Asia capacity utilization will fall to 60 percent in
2002 from its 1996 level of 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, DRI pointed out that with the sluggish growth and
severe competition that will characterize the mature markets -
Western Europe, North America and Japan - during the coming years,
the over capacity issue should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
In Western Europe through the 1990s, 1.9 million units will be
added to car capacity production, the report forecast.
</P>
<P>
The UK and Germany will absorb 60 percent of the capacity
expansion, and Japanese manufacturers will account for close to 40
percent of the total additional units. As a result there will be a
slow recovery in capacity utilization.
</P>
<P>
With a flat sales market, North America is in the best position
capacity-wise, according to the forecast.
</P>
<P>
Utilization is forecasted to grow from 88 percent to 93 percent
in 2002 while Japan will see little improvement in capacity
utilization improving only one percentage point to 68 percent by
2002.
</P>
<P>
Schwarz emphasised that over capacity is not an insurmountable
issue, saying that "increasing the flexibility of assembly plant
to meet market demands and respond more quickly to unpredictable
changes in the global marketplace is key to confronting over
capacity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
