<HEADLINE> Iraq Seeks Better Economic Ties with Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Jordan will strengthen
bilateral economic cooperation, said Adnan el-Goodsy, chairman of
the Iraqi Industrial Union, here today.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Jordanian economic officials for better economic
ties, Goodsy said Iraq's relations with any other country will
not affect the "distinguished" Jordanian-Iraqi ties.
</P>
<P>
Goodsy's visit came when the sanction-ravaged Iraq is seeking
cooperation with Arab neighbors and lifting of U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan will be one of the first countries to benefit from the
lifting of the U.N. sanctions," said the chairman, who expressed
appreciation for Jordan's efforts to alleviate Iraqi people's
suffering incurred by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan promised to provide more facilities in its Red
Sea port Aqaba, the only way that commodities can be imported into
Iraq, to improve the conditions for food and medicine into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq hopes for an increase of 50 million U.S. dollars in its
trade protocol with Jordan now estimated at 255 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 13 Jordanian companies have received
permissions from the U.N. Sanction Committee to export
detergents, cooking oil and medicine worth more than 35 million
dollars to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was one of the most important economic partners for
Iraq before the Gulf crisis, but it distanced itself from Baghdad
in an effort to end its isolation from the Arab world and the West.
</P>
<P>
In the beginning of this year, the amount of oil supplied
free by Iraq for Jordan was raised from 250 million dollars
to 300 million dollars. 
</P>
