<HEADLINE> UK's Trade Deficit Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain's trade performance improved
in March with no sign of damage from the strong pound in world
foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics took City economists by
surprise with news of a decline in the gap between export earnings
and the bill for imports from 771 million pounds (1233.6 million
US dollars) to 671 million pounds (1073.6 US dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
The trade gap with Europe shrank to just 20 million pounds (32
million US dollars) from 290 million pounds (464 million US
dollars) in February, making it the second time in nine months
that a position of near balance has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
City analysts had warned for some months that exports would be
hit by the strong pound. But the latest official figures show the
trade picture in Britain is improving.
</P>
<P>
Dharshini David, an economist at HSBC, said there were few
clear signs that the strength of sterling was damaging the trade
position yet.
</P>
<P>
However, most economists still expect the damage to show up
later this year, following survey evidence indicating declining
export orders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
