<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Community Pressures Bosnia Leaders on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINTRA, Portugal, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The international
community urged on Friday Bosnia's elected authorities to
implement the Dayton peace agreement in full or face a number of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
This was voiced at a meeting of the Steering Board of the Peace
Implementation Council(IPC), created after the signing of the
Dayton Agreement which ended the Bosnia war 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held in the Portugese town of Sintra, was
participated by the countries involved in helping implementing the
Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
Three members of Bosnia's rotating presidency - Alija
Izetbegovic, a Muslim, Dresimir Zubak, a Croat, and Momcilo
Krajisnik, a Serb, also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Carl Bildt, the outgoing international envoy to Bosnia, told a
new conference after the meeting that there was "strong
endorsement of the principal" at the meeting that international
assistance with economic reconstruction should be conditional upon
full compliance with the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
A declaration issued after the meeting said that sanctions
would be considered if the new three-man Bosnian presidency had
not appointed or confirmed new ambassadors by August 1 this year
to represent the entire country.
</P>
<P>
From January 1998, the declaration said, only cars with new
Bosnian registration plates would be allowed across international
borders
</P>
<P>
It warned that existing nationalist flags and other symbols
would no longer be recognized after September 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Economic aid would be cut off to "those municipalities which
continue to tolerate indicted persons working in a public
capacity".
</P>
<P>
The meeting also called on the Bosnian authorities to take
necessary actions to reform property laws, pass citizenship laws,
restructure police forces, and hand over indicted war criminals.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced that a Donor's Conference was planned to
be held in Brussels at senior official level on June 24 this year.
</P>
<P>
The United States, France and Britain, the main contributors to
SFOR,the international peace force in Bosnia, fear failure to make
progress in implementing the civilian aspects of Dayton Agreement
could see Bosnia slip back into war after SFOR's mandate expires
next July or force them to keep troops there indefinitely.
</P>
</TEXT>
