<HEADLINE> Megan Trial Defendant Found Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Jesse Timmendequas has been
convicted on all charges and could face the death penalty for
kidnapping, raping and killing his 7-year-old neighbor, Megan
Kanka, whose death gave rise to laws warning communities about sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
Jurors at the trial that lasted 17 days in New Jersey
deliberated for just over four hours spread over two days before
reaching their verdict today.
</P>
<P>
The same jury, selected in neighboring Hunterdon County because
of heavy pre-trial publicity in Mercer County where the crime
occurred, must now decide the sentence. Mercer County Superior
Court Judge Andrew Smithson told jurors he would have to discuss
scheduling of the penalty phase with lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Megan disappeared in July 1994. A few hours later, Timmendequas
led police to her body in a park.
</P>
<P>
Timmendequas, a twice-convicted child molester, was sharing a
house with two men he had met in New Jersey's prison for sex
offenders. Neighbors in Hamilton Square, a quiet suburb of
Trenton, were not aware of the three roommates' past crimes.
</P>
<P>
The case inspired "Megan's laws" in New Jersey, in other states
and Congress requiring sex offenders to register with police and
community notification of the presence of those deemed to be
dangerous. Those laws are facing challenges in state and federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said that Timmendequas lured the girl into his
home, fondled her and strangled her with a belt when she began
struggling and threatened to tell on him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
