<HEADLINE> Work or Leave, A Question for Egyptians in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A total of some 300,000 Egyptians
working in Jordan should either obtain valid work permits or leave
the country with the current exemption of fines as of today.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed between Jordan and Egypt in
March, from April 1 on, all Egyptian workers found in violation
will be deported or face legal actions by Jordan's Labor Ministry.
</P>
<P>
This is in light of the government's decision to cut down the
number of Egyptians working in the economic recession-hit
country. It was believed their over presence has incurred
unemployment among Jordanians and loss of foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment among the Jordanians is largely due to those who
shun jobs (which are then) taken by non-Jordanians," said
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali on May 18 while
meeting Minister of Labor Saleh Khasawneh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a bank official said that foreign labor here
usually remitted some 28 million dollars a quarter out of Jordan
and a large part of it was remitted by the Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
This made up some one 15th of the money remitted back into
Jordan by Jordanian expatriates, said Ahmad Mustafa, executive
director of the Research and Studies Department at the Central
Bank of Jordan, on May 24 in an interview.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 Egyptian are working in Jordan and most of them
illegally, according to officials here. Some had demonstrated the
desire to return home but were unable to do so as heavy fines were
levied for staying in the kingdom with expired visas.
</P>
<P>
The workers were then granted a grace period ending today to
leave Jordan without penalty or obtain, by paying an annual fee of
some 140 U.S. dollars, work permits, issued by the Jordanian Labor
Ministry and approved by the Egyptian embassy in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Labor Ministry issued 42,796 work permits to
non-Jordanian workers in 1996, down from 94,333 in 1995, thus
strictly complying with measures announced by the Cabinet in
1996 to cut the number of guest workers in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
A 1996 government order also closed 16 different occupations
to non-Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt have enjoyed close cooperation since 1984 when
Jordan became the first Arab state to resume diplomatic relations
with Egypt. Most Arab League members cut off their ties with
Cairo in 1979 to protest the Israeli-Egyptian peace treaty.

31/05/97 15:6 GMT

=05311740
NNNN
23:18 23:18 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
