<HEADLINE> Top Palestinian Negotiators in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- With no apparent progress in
breaking the Mideast crisis in sight, two Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) negotiators held consultations with Egyptian
officials here today on Egypt's efforts to save the flagging
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, PNA minister of local administration and senior
negotiator, and Hassan Asfour, coordinator of negotiations
affairs, arrived here on Friday night for talks with senior
Egyptian officials on the latest development in the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came a day before Osama el-Baz, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak's political advisor, is due to go to Israel again in
a bid to bring the Israelis and the Palestinians back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz, who has been shuttling between the two sides since
Tuesday's summit between Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu, is expected in Jerusalem on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Intensive Egyptian diplomatic efforts to revive the Mideast
peace process climaxed last Tuesday when Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak met with Netanyahu in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of
Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership, during a weekly meeting in
Ramallah of the West Bank on Friday night, voiced welcome and
support of the Egyptian bid to reactivate the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in an interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arab
radio today, Arafat's advisor Ahmed Tibi downplayed the
possibility of holding a Palestinian-Israeli summit, something
Mubarak had hoped to arrange in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks broke down when Israel
began building a new settlement in Har Homa, a Jewish quarter in
Arab East Jerusalem in March. The PNA has made its return to the
negotiating table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary
policy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was reportedly floating a five-point plan to persuade
the two sides to the negotiations, which includes a temporary halt
of settlement activities in Jerusalem and the West Bank and the
resumption of Palestinian-Israeli security coordination. 
