<HEADLINE> Japanese Capital Injected in Home-funded Car Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Guizhou Yunque (Lark) Car
Corporation, the only major automaker with no foreign capital,
recently settled an agreement to form a joint venture with a
Japanese company.
</P>
<P>
After five years of contracts, owners of the corporation, the
China Guizhou Aviation Industrial Corporation and China Guizhou
Joint Automotive Industrial Corporation (CGJAIC), signed a letter
of intent with Japanese Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. during a recent
trade fair held in this capital of southwest China's Guizhou
Province.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Chinese side is to pour 306 million
yuan (36.87 million US dollars) in the new joint venture, taking
51 percent of stake. And the Japanese side agreed to provide 294
million yuan (35.42 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new venture is set to have a manufacturing capacity of
10,000 compact cars.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang Binyan, general manager of CGJAIC, even
though the venture has already been named by the Chinese
government as one of the country's eight major car production
projects, the shortage of capital still restricted its
expansion.
</P>
<P>
"The new company will carry out technical renovation on the
existing production lines in a bid to produce and sell quality
Yunque cars," he said.
</P>
<P>
The company will also increase its local contents proportion to
reduce costs and hone its competitive edge in the marketplace,
Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Compact cars are best-selling models in China's auto
market. Other major compact car model, the Alto, is produced by a
joint venture between a local automaker and Japan's Isuzu
Corporation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
