<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai-Tibet Highway Plays Big Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Qinghai-Tibet Highway has been
playing an important role in the growth of local economy in
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region, the country's only
provincial region that has no rail route.
</P>
<P>
Some 85 percent of the autonomous region's goods and materials
are moved in and out by road; all heavy equipment needed to build
large projects has to be trucked through the highway to reach
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The highway has resulted in the mushrooming of a number of new
towns in Tibet which are dotted throughout the grasslands, and
local products, including livestock, have found their way into
inland markets.
</P>
<P>
Construction began in 1953 on the road, more than 1,100 km in
length, which extends from Gormu City, Qinghai Province, to Lhasa,
the capital of Tibet. In 1984, the central government invested
billions of yuan to upgrade it to an asphalt-covered motorway.
</P>
<P>
Snaking along at an average height of 4,500 m, it is the
highest road in the world. Bad weather frequent the area, where
winter temperatures can dive as low as -40 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
After years of work, the Qinghai-Tibet Highway has been built
into a second-grade model, over which vehicles can travel at
speeds as high as 100 kmh.
</P>
<P>
A project is currently underway to tackle such problems as
foundation-distortion and sinking in the frozen-earth area which
covers an over 700 km-section of the road. It is the second such
project, costing more than 900 million yuan (108 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
An isolation layer will be added to solve the frozen-earth
problem, according to experts with the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970531.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Opposition Rally Broken up, Causing Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan anti-riot police today
dispersed a banned rally of opposition parties asking for
constitutional reforms in downtown Nairobi, causing hours of
turmoil in which at least dozens of people were injured.
</P>
<P>
Heavy-armed police drove more than 1,000 opposition
sympathizers out of the central Uhuru Park, the planned venue of
the rally, in panic after wielding billies and clubs, and firing
tear-gas grenades.
</P>
<P>
Police helicopters circled around over the center of the city,
where all business came to a complete standstill, to coordinate
and move dozens of trucks of Kenyan polices and security forces.
</P>
<P>
There were fierce running battles between the stone-throwing
crowd and the police, who protected themselves with shields and
helmets.
</P>
<P>
Cavalries were also deployed in downtown to dispel the
demonstrators, who repeated shouting like that:"Moi must go",
"change Now!"
</P>
<P>
Stones scattered fully around some streets. Windows of several
shops were smashed.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leaders today also held a press briefing,
calling for opening of a constitutional conference immediately.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have been putting pressures on
President Daniel arap Moi to conduct constitutional reforms
before the forthcoming general elections, while Moi insists he
will only do that after the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leaders call for a change of the clause,
demanding the future president get more than 50 percent of the
total votes nationwide, otherwise form a coalition government.
But the call has already been refused by Moi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government issued a statement on Friday, banning
today's rally, the second rally organized by the four main
opposition parties in the eastern African country -- Democratic
Party, Ford Kenya, Ford Asili and the National Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the conveners of the meeting had
neither sought nor been given any licence and it is therefore "
illegal for any person to attend such a meeting."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan governmental forces banned and then broke up the
first rally of opposition parties earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
