<HEADLINE> Italy Beats China in World League Volleyball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- World top-ranked Italy trounced
China in straights sets in the first round of the World Volleyball
League Group B preliminaries here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Italy, two-time world champion and world cup holder, met no
challenge from the hosts before winning with three identical 15-6
in one hour and 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese spikers, led by the newly-appointed coach Wang
Jiawei, were apparently no match with the Italians, who won the
wolrd league champions for five times but finished second last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Italians, spearheaded by two-time World Champion Andrea
Giani, raced to a 7-1 lead soon after the action.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were deadlocked at 14-6, exchanging service for
some ten times before Italy took it 15-6.
</P>
<P>
Italy then pulled away in the following two sets with their
powerful attacks, well-knit defences, strong service and solid
blocks.
</P>
<P>
"Our service is very effective, and our blocks very good, "
said Italy's head coach Bebeto de Freitas, who just took over the
Italians from legend Argentine Julio Velasco early this year.
</P>
<P>
Freitas, who had coached his native Brazilian national squad
for 10 years, was very happy with the win.
</P>
<P>
"We started well in the first and I hope it will be also good
in the second," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's head coach Wang, a former national who led China to a
record fifth in the World Cup tournament, said: "The loss reflects
the real gap between China and world's first-class teams. I hope
it will be helpful to us."
</P>
<P>
"It's a good and expected result because we only assembled and
trained together less than half a month. We need time," Wang added.
</P>
<P>
The two teams will play their second match on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China, who was drawn in Group B with Italy, Yugoslavia and
Spain, had played against Yugoslavia and Spain twice each on the
road, only to be defeated in all six outings.
</P>
<P>
Teams from 12 countries and regions compete in the World League
in three groups. Each team plays six home-and-away matches through
June 22. The two top teams from each group will advance to the
final round scheduled to begin on June 30 in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
