<HEADLINE> Children's Gymnastics Show Held in Tian'anmen Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 five- and
six-year-olds from both inland areas and Hong Kong staged a lively
gymnastics show in Tian'anmen Square in Beijing today to celebrate
International Children's Day and greet the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
For an hour in the cool morning air, the kids demonstrated the
newly-created Chinese Basic Exercises for Children.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the square, printed slogans such as "Building up
strong physique and fostering a new generation," and "Entering the
21st with healthy physique and minds," fluttered from colored
balloons.
</P>
<P>
A countdown board on the east side of the square showed that
only 31 days remain until the return of Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of pigeons, which symbolize peace and happiness, were
set free into the sky when the children began their routines.
</P>
<P>
The basic exercises are designed to improve children's physical
health and help them develop an awareness of unity and interest in
group activities, said Li Shiming, an official with the China
National Committee on Care for Children.
</P>
<P>
"Today's children need more exercise," Li said. "A recent
survey shows that about ten percent of the children in big cities
are overweight, while many are too thin."
</P>
<P>
He said that the basic exercises, both amusing and easy to
learn, are suitable for children between the ages of three and six.
</P>
<P>
China has many one-child families, due to the state's family
planning policies, he said, children in those families easily
become self-centered because they receive too much attention from
their parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the group exercises can help them to learn
many things, he said, including how to treat each other politely
and behave well. More than 100,000 preschool children around the
country are doing such kind of exercises.
</P>
<P>
Today's activity was jointly organized by the China National
Committee on Care for Children, the All-China Women's Federation,
the China Gymnastics Association and other units.
</P>
<P>
A group of children from Hong Kong demonstrated "Chair
Exercises" in the square today.
</P>
<P>
"I had been wondering if my son could do it well," said Ko Yin
Fan, mother of six-year-old Law Wai Yee. "But everything turned out
all right."
</P>
<P>
"It's the first time we have come to Beijing, and my son is
really excited," she said. "He likes this city."
</P>
<P>
She said she hopes they can come to Beijing again after July
1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
