<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Post Found on Beijing's Northwestern Outskirts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The ruins of an ancient post have
been discovered on Beijing's outlying northwestern outskirts.
</P>
<P>
The post, named Yulinbao located in Yanqing County, is the
oldest and the best preserved site of its kind ever found in the
Beijing area.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the post was important in the Yuan
(1271-1368), Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) Dynasties, and
a number of poets mentioned the place in their work.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that Empress Dowager Cixi and Emperor
Guangxu of the late Qing dynasty used the post as a resting place
on their way out of Beijing, when the city was overtaken in the
year 1900 by the Eight-Power Allied Forces, or the intruding
troops sent by the Western powers including Britain, the United
States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Many cultural relics remain in the post, which has 800 meters
of city wall and 34 ancient buildings intact, and in which 257
relics were found.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the post is of great importance for the
research into the history of posts and communications in the
region, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The site is expected to be developed into a tourist attraction,
according to sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
