<HEADLINE> Large Car Project Completes Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Six years' construction of a
large car manufacturing joint venture came to an end today in
northeast China's Changchun, dubbed "China's Detroit."
</P>
<P>
FAW-Volkswagen Automobile Co. is a joint venture involving
China's First Auto Works Corporation (FAW) and the German-based
Volkswagen Group, in which FAW holds 60 percent of stake and the
German partner takes the rest.
</P>
<P>
At a total cost of 10.77 billion yuan, the project is designed
with a production capacity of 150,000 cars, 270,000 engines and
180,000 gearboxes after first-phase construction.
</P>
<P>
Started in 1991, the venture in the same year turned out its
first batch of products, the Jetta cars.
</P>
<P>
As of today, the venture has manufactured 100,000 Audi cars. A
new Jetta model with a new powertrain system has also been in
batch production.
</P>
<P>
Jetta has become one of the best-selling models in China's
auto market. 
</P>
