<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Calls for Establishment of Tobacco Free World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) today called upon all African governments, private and
public sectors, young and old people to redouble their efforts
for a tobacco free world.
</P>
<P>
The call came from a statement issued by the WHO office in
Addis Ababa to mark the 10th anniversary of the World No Tobacco
day which falls on today.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged African countries and member states of the
WHO in particular to take a retrospective look at our
achievements over the past 10 years in regard to the control of
tobacco use and project themselves into the future to see what
remains to be done, in order to overcome this scourge.
</P>
<P>
The statement listed the fact that the United Nations system
has taken necessary measures to control tobacco use in the world,
such as: WHO has prohibited smoking on its premises since more
than ten years, the World Bank and its associates no longer give
bank loans for the cultivation and promotion of tobacco, FAO has
been helping countries whose economy is dependent on tobacco to
find substitute produce to replace the cultivation and marketing
of tobacco, the International Civil Aviation Organization has
since 1996 requested all airlines worldwide to prohibit smoking
on their flights.
</P>
<P>
It said that in the African region, over 39 percent of the WHO
member states have already adopted laws, decrees or regulations
prohibiting tobacco use in public places or buildings such as
hospitals, schools, cinema halls, as well as in public transport.
</P>
<P>
However, it pointed out that the number of smokers in an
african country ranges between 10 percent and 50 percent of the
population depending on the country.
</P>
<P>
''Youths, boys and girls, are still lured by the lifestyles of
smokers often idealized by the mass media as examples of social
success,'' the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
''Unfortunately, in Africa, cigarettes are sold without
restrications or mandatory warning on the attendant health
hazards. No mention is made of the different ingredients and
additivies, including of the worst kinds, used in the manufacture
of cigarettes,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement emphased that all these constitute serious
obstacles to efficient and effecitve tobacco control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
