<HEADLINE> Volunteers Protect Cultural Relics in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 people in Jinxian
county in east China's Zhejiang Province have been volunteering to
protect local cultural relics in the county that has suffered from
tomb robberies and cultural relics smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers learn laws and regulations on cultural relics,
patrol local historical sites, and inform various departments if
they find new cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Jinxian is the site of the ancient Jinzi State of the Shang
Dynasty (16th - 11th Century BC) and has spent a large sum of
money in the past decade on protecting its historical sites.
</P>
<P>
The county spent ten million yuan last year to renovate a
temple of Liang Shanbo, magistrate of the county in the Eastern
Jin Dynasty (317-420) who was the inspiration for one of China's
most famous legendary figure in 'The Story of Butterfly', about
Liang Shanbo and Zhu Yingtai, a Chinese version of Romeo and
Juliet.
</P>
<P>
Other relics include Tashan Dam, one of the four largest water
conservation projects in ancient China; a 134-sq-km lake dug in
the Tang Dynasty (618-907); and more than 200 stone sculptures
that are the largest group of stone sculptures from the Southern
Song Dynasty (1127-1279) that are still in existence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
