<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislative Council Commission Bill Tabled to HK PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, China, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Legislative Council
Commission (Amendment) Bill, which aims to facilitate
administrative support to the legislature of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) after July 1, was tabled to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) here today.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy coordination of the Chief
Executive's Office of the HKSAR, moved the draft bill to the PLC's
full sitting for first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that under Article 8 of the Basic Law, the existing
Legislative Council Commission Ordinance will continue to be in
force after June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure the continued application of the ordinance from July
1 and to make transitional arrangements arising from the
establishment of the PLC and its supporting structure," Suen
noted, the Working Group on Administrative Matters under the PLC
had earlier reviewed the ordinance and recommended a number of
modifications.
</P>
<P>
These recommendations were adopted at a PLC meeting on May 17
and the bill seeks to implement the recommendations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for the adapted definitions of the
"Legislative Council", "Legislative Council Secretariat" and
"Legislative Council Commission", with changes to certain terms
and references also being made.
</P>
<P>
It states that several existing references such as "Crown" and
"standing orders" shall be changed to "Government" and "rules of
procedure" respectively so as to be consistent with the Basic Law
and to reflect the situation after Hong Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
The existing Legislative Council Commission was established in
April 1994 to provides through the secretariat the council
administrative support and services to the Hong Kong Legislature.
</P>
<P>
Transitional arrangements are made for members of the working
group, which performs functions similar to those of the existing
Legislative Council Commission, to become members of the PLC
commission from July 1 and to supervise the operation of the
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The bill proposes that the membership of the PLC commission be
increased to a total of not more than 13, including three
ex-officio members -- the president of the PLC, and the chairman
and deputy chairman of the PLC House Committee.
</P>
<P>
The bill also seeks to facilitate convergence of the
administrative set-up and support services to the PLC with the
existing Legislative Council Secretariat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
