<HEADLINE> Planned Vaccination Benefits Children in Hunan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Four million children in
central-south China's Hunan Province have benefited from
vaccination programs, as proved by a drop of 90 percent over the
past decade in the incidence of such common infant diseases as
diphtheria, pertussis, and measles.
</P>
<P>
According to an evaluation by the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) and the Chinese Ministry of Health, more than 97
percent of the children in Hunan have been inoculated against
these diseases.
</P>
<P>
No cases of polio have been reported in Hunan over the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
Hunan started to build a cold storage system for vaccines back
in 1984, and set up the first inoculation program that covered
over 60 counties and cities the following year. The province-wide
planned vaccination system was completed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Hunan has appropriated 2.5 million yuan (300,000 US
dollars) annually to purchase the polio vaccine, which has been
used to inoculate 20 million people and caused the vaccination
rate for the disease to exceed 99 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province initiated a three-year project to add
2.5 million yuan (301,000 US dollars) each year for the renewal of
cold storage equipment for vaccines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
