<HEADLINE> Another River Port Opens to Foreign Vessels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A Honduras-registered ship today
set sail from Chenglingji Port north of central China's Hunan
Province to the city of Nagoya in Japan, marking the opening of
the port to foreign vessels.
</P>
<P>
Historically a transport hub to link China's vast interior areas
with Shanghai, a key sea port, via the Yangtze River, the port is
located at the strategic intersection between the Yangtze River
and Dongting Lake, China's second largest freshwater lake.
</P>
<P>
Two 5,000-tonnage berths have already been built in the
port. Other facilities necessary for the opening, including a
customs house, commodity inspection, animal and plant quarantines
and frontier inspection, have also been set up. State port
administration authorities earlier this year approved the port as
Class-A port for foreign vessels.
</P>
<P>
Set to handle six million tons of cargo a year, the port is
considered by local officials to be beneficial for the overall
opening of the inland province, as well as for neighboring
localities. 
