<HEADLINE> Youngsters Enthusiastic about China's Anti-Tobacco Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Primary and middle school students
in the Chinese capital today challenged their counterparts across
the country to become the first generation of non-smokers in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of 1,000 "Smoke-free Schools" in Beijing issued
a proposal to put a stop to teenage smoking in a bid to protect
people's health and the environment, and to contribute to the
nation's development in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"As the new generation of the 21st century, we should devote
ourselves to China's anti-tobacco campaign. We should not take
cigarettes, encourage smokers to kick the habit, and stop illegal
smoking in public places," they said in the proposal issued today,
the tenth "Worldwide No-Tobacco Day."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the group presented to the organizing committee of
the Tenth World Conference on Tobacco and Health a 100-meter-long
list of 200,000 Beijing students who signed their names and wrote
anti-tobacco slogans in support of the global anti-smoking drive
and the conference, scheduled to be held here in August.
</P>
<P>
"We should always attach importance to the control of teenage
smoking, because this group will make the number of smokers in
China higher," said Ming Lu, an official who is in charge of
smoking-control work at the National Patriotic Hygiene Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Of the 350 million smokers in China, five million are under age
18.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Chen Minzhang has warned that if measures
are not taken immediately, two million smokers will die from
smoking-related illnesses annually by the year 2020, and many of
them will be young people.
</P>
<P>
In order to curb the growing rate of teenage smoking, the
Ministry of Health and the Chinese Association on Smoking and
Health have urged primary and middle schools across the country to
take action.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, 1,000 schools, or one-third of the total number,
have become smoke-free.
</P>
<P>
About one million young people, responding to a call by the
Soong Ching Ling Foundation, have taken part in no-smoking
activities for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The foundation appeals to youngsters not to smoke, not to sell
or buy cigarettes, to tell their families to stop smoking or smoke
less, and to discourage people from smoking in public places.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
