<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Likely to Intervene in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- There are signs that the
Nigerian-led West African Peace-keeping Force known as ECOMOG may
intervene in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Following a silence-breaking presidency statement on Thursday
condemning the coup in Sierra Leone, Nigerian Foreign Minister
Tom Ikimi on Friday re-affirmed his government's support for
outsted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Contributing to a debate on Sierra Leone at the meeting of
foreign ministers of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in
Harare, Ikimi described Kabbah as "a great leader, upright in
stature and a man of peace".
</P>
<P>
He blamed the west countries for pressing Sierra leone into
the last election without allowing it to address the inherent
problems that led to the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Many people doubted at that time if the necessary conditions
for election existed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi disclosed that as the Chairman of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), Nigerian Head of State, General
Sani Abacha has been holding intensive sub-regional consultations
to ensure a quick restoration of peace, stability and
installation of a legitimate government in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Ikimi told BBC that Nigeria deplores "the
loss of lives and the wanton destruction and looting of property
which have accompanied the incident in Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
"We have a responsibility as a country, Nigeria and General
Abacha as the Chairman of the ECOWAS to assist Sierra Leone to
resolve its conflicts and find a durable solution."
</P>
<P>
Since May 27, 1,300 ECOMOG soldiers in Liberia have been sent
to Freetown. Reports said that they have been involved in
evacuating forign nations.
</P>
<P>
Before the coup, Nigeria already had at least a battalion in
Freetown to help train Sierra Leonean troops in accordance with
to an agreement signed between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Nigerian soldiers were involved in
the fighting against the coupists and in helping President Kabbah
to flee his country, as they have been deployed to guard the
presidential house.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian media reported today that the United
States government has given its backing to any action by Nigeria
to restore the legitimate government of Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
In Freetown, the coup leader, Paul Jonny Koroma said in an
interview with BBC on Friday that he received signals that the
Nigerian government had instructed the ECOMOG troops to attack
under a code name.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that Sierra Leone will resist any foreign invasion of
its territory.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council set up
by the coupist ordered the immediate close of the country's sea
and land border.
</P>
<P>
The order also banned all aircraft from flying over the
territory of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The coup in Sierra Leone has been widely condemned by the
United Nations, the OAU and many countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
