<HEADLINE> 98 Percent of Kuwaiti Territories Cleared of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait said today that 98
percent of its territories are free of land-mines and other
explosives left by the Gulf War in 1991 which have claimed the
lives of nearly 1,800 victims so far.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Am published
today, Kuwaiti land forces engineering corps commander Colonel
Jassem Al-Sumait said so far 1.03 million mines, including 567,650
anti-tank mines left by the Iraqi occupation during the Gulf War,
have been removed, neutralized or detonated.
</P>
<P>
He said 98 percent of Kuwaiti territories, including Failaka
Island, had been cleared. The remaining uncleared areas include
the oil lakes, some inside desert areas, and certain coastal
locations.
</P>
<P>
Soon after Kuwait was liberated by the U.S.-led allied forces
in 1991, Kuwait was divided into eight areas and contracts were
awarded to eight companies and armies for demining hundreds of
thousands of various types of mines.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sumait said 53 people were killed and 164 others from
various nationalities were wounded in removing or detonating the
mines.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Kuwaiti Red Crescent Society Barjas Al-Barjas
said recently that "the victims of mines in Kuwait amounted to
4,000 civilians, of whom 1,700 died and the injured people was
2,300."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "although we removed most of the mines, we
called upon people to be aware especially in coastal and desert
areas."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait so far has refused to forgive Iraq for the military
incursion with no sign in sight of resuming ties between the two
neighbors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
