<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Region Building Five Agricultural Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, which is rich in water, soil, light and heat
resources suitable for farming, is building five production bases
for cotton, grains, livestock, beets, and fruits to increase
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the State decided to help build cotton and grain bases
in Xinjiang by providing more than 10 billion yuan in financing
for the next few years. The region is also taking advantage of
China's westward shift in economic development to promote
agriculture and help narrow the east-west gap in earnings.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has been China's largest cotton producer for years and
produced 940,000 tons of cotton last year, accounting for nearly a
third of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
Last year's grain production was 7.8 billion kg, with
per-head grain output rising from 15th place in the nation
to fifth among China's provinces.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region is one of the country's five largest
grassland areas, and raises the largest number of sheep. This
makes the region the second largest sugar beet grower, after
Heilongjiang in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
The region is also home to many kinds of fruit, with an output of
1.16 million tons of fruit last year, three times the nation's per
capita average. The Korla pear and Turfan grapes sell well both in
China and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
