<HEADLINE> Alert Urged to Tackle Spread of Measles in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's leading medical
academic called for a comprehensive measles vaccination program to
tackle an expected epidemic of the disease next year.
</P>
<P>
Associate Dean of Hong Kong University's Medical Faculty Lau
Yu-long said the outbreak could put 1.3 million children and
teenagers at risk while criticizing the government for lack of
action.
</P>
<P>
Director of Health Chan Fung Fu-chun has called an emergency
meeting of the policy-making Immunization Committee for next
Tuesday, as a 10-year cycle of the disease appears to be reaching
a peak.
</P>
<P>
Today's Hong Kong Standard reported that the last measles
epidemic hit Hong Kong in 1988, infecting 3,162 patients and
killing eight. From January to mid-May this year, 142 cases were
recorded, exceeding the 1996 total of 110 cases.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department's move follows a wave of criticism
against its failure to combat this year's epidemic of German
measles, or rubella, which had infected 2,111 mostly young people
by mid-May, more than double the 892 cases reported for the whole
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, rubella claimed its first life in Hong Kong
with the death of a 16-year-old schoolboy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
