<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Privatize 61 State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
earmarked 61 state-owned enterprises for sale in a bid to speed up
the slow pace of privatization, according to official sources
here.
</P>
<P>
The government statistics showed that only 12 industries were
privatized in the last four year and not a single enterprise was
privatized in the last 11 months.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the newly-appointed Chairman of the
Privatization Board Kazi Zafarullah was dissatisfied with the slow
pace of privatization.
</P>
<P>
"The Privatization Board will act like a shop from now on," the
chairman was quoted by the sources while he was talking with a
group of businessmen recently.
</P>
<P>
The government is selling majority of its shares in nine public
limited companies through the stock market and the government will
get around 2.5 million U.S. dollars this year from the sale, said
Kazi Zafarullah, adding that the board now has the power to sell
industries worth upto 100 million taka (about 2.5 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the government cannot continue to sustain
an annual loss of about 2.5 billion taka (about 625 million
dollars) in the name of subsidy to the state-owned enterprises
(SOEs), said Zafarullah.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SOEs are also responsible for the present acute
liquidity crisis in the banks because a lion's portion of bad debt
amounting to 130 billion taka (about 3.25 billion dollars) has
been caused by them, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
