<HEADLINE> Cemetery Attracts More Overseas Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 noted figures
from China and the rest of the world have been buried at a
cemetery beside the Western Imperial Tombs of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911) in Yixian county in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The cemetery, which became famous in 1995 when the ashes of Pu
Yi, the last emperor of the Qing Dynasty were moved there, was not
completed until 1994. It covers an area of 20 hectares and has
over 50,000 burial spots.
</P>
<P>
The Western imperial tombs of the Qing Dynasty, Qingxiling,
contain four emperors and hundreds of imperial concubines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
