<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The pilot of the last civilian flight out of Sierra Leone on
Friday night described how he plucked 400 Westerners, including
200 Britons, to safety from the war-torn African state as gunfire
echoed across the runway.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Microsoft, the world's largest software company, is planning
to establish in the next few months a European research center in
England, which is the first of its kind outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- David Blunkett, secretary of state for Education and
Employment, told head teachers on Friday that he would not bow to
their demands for the removal of Chris Woodhead, chief inspector
of schools, who has attacked progressive teaching methods and
exposed failing schools.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- The voters of France look likely to turn decisively left
tomorrow, plunging the country into five years of shared
left-right government and heaping further doubts on the timetable
for the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- The British government on Friday brushed aside the first
protest from its natural supporters when David Blunkett, the
country's Education and Employment Secretary, rejected a unanimous
vote of no confidence by head teachers on Chris Woodhead, the
chief inspector of schools. 
</P>
