<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Starts Visit to New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND (New Zealand), May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
Zhu Rongji arrived here this evening to start a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement upon his arrival, he said the visit "is
aimed at strengthening high-level exchanges, enhancing mutual
understanding and promoting mutually beneficial cooperation so as
to propel the existing friendly relations and cooperation up to a
new level."
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic relations between China and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that over the past 25 years and recent years in
particular, bilateral relations between the two countries have
developed steadily and their mutually-beneficial cooperation in
the political, economic and trade, scientific and technological,
cultural and educational fields have yielded positive results.
</P>
<P>
While China is a major agricultural country, New Zealand is
advanced in agriculture and animal husbandry. "The two countries
are highly complementary in the economic field and enjoy great
potentials and broad prospects for economic cooperation and
trade," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
To developed bilateral relations not only conforms with the
fundamental interests and common desires of the two countries and
two peoples, but also contributes to regional peace and stability,
he stated.
</P>
<P>
In the next three days, the Chinese vice premier will visit a
dairy company and an agricultural research center. He will also
meet NZ government leaders to exchange views on matters of common
interests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
