<HEADLINE> Taliban Recaptures Strategic Northern Afghan Town: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
claimed to have recaptured Jabul Siraj, a strategic town located
about 77 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Taliban troops led by Ahmad Shah Masood had taken Jabul
Siraj on Friday and were heading toward nearby Charikar, capital
of Parwan province, when the Taliban launched its counter
offensive.
</P>
<P>
The former defense chief in the Rabbani government, Ahmed Shah
Massood, is commanding the anti-Taliban troops, according to
reports reaching here today from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Taliban sources as saying that the student
militia repelled a massive attack by Massood in Jabul Siraj and
the northern Salang highway.
</P>
<P>
Both Massood's troops and the Taliban are reported to have
suffered heavy losses in the heavy fighting during the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taliban forces are also under heavy attack in
northern Afghanistan, where they are battling opposition forces
who had thrown them out of Mazar-e-Sharif last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Taliban soldiers have reportedly been taken
prisoner.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban retreated from Mazar-e-Sharif on Wednesday, just
five days after their troops entered the city without facing any
resistance. It was the first time the Taliban were forced out of a
city it had captured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
