<HEADLINE> Vietnam Expects Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is likely to record another
ample rice harvest if no abnormal weather affects the
winter-spring crop over the next few weeks, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development predicted
that an estimated 13 million tons of rice could be harvested,
about one million tons more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is calling on provincial authorities in northern
Vietnam to help farmers gather in their crop grown in the
low-lying fields in time as more rainfalls have been forecast in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in southern Vietnam, who harvested an estimated seven
million tons of paddy from their 1.25 million hectares of
winter-spring crop, have already sown and transplanted more than
1.24 million hectares of summer-autumn rice, with the Mekong River
Delta making up one million hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
