<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's 2-day Weekend Decision Creates Mixed Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government's
announcement granting a two-day weekly holiday on Friday and
Saturday has created mixed reactions in Bangladesh, mostly
negative in the business community.
</P>
<P>
The government on Thursday declared Friday and Saturday as
weekly holidays instead of only Friday, with the objective to
"increase efficiency and productivity, save expenditure on account
of fuel and check pollution."
</P>
<P>
However, major trade bodies were critical of the government
decision, claiming that a poor country like Bangladesh could not
economically afford a two-day weekly holiday.
</P>
<P>
"I find no rationality for a two-day weekly holiday in a
country like Bangladesh where productivity is the lowest and which
have a vast pool of unemployed people," said Samson Chowdhury,
president of the Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(MCCI).
</P>
<P>
The MCCI president said that there was no consultation with his
chamber before the announcement. "It will be a problem for the
private sector since the number of public holiday in the country
is more than those in America."
</P>
<P>
Mahbub Jamil, president of the Foreign Investors Chamber of
Commerce and Industry (FICCI), shared a similar view. "With the
new decision, we'll be going backward, not forward. We can't
welcome it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The FICCI, which represents the multinational companies doing
business in Bangladesh, was demanding Sunday as weekly holiday as
the business community having international connections often miss
business links with their partners.
</P>
<P>
Some businessmen, including Chairman of the Bangladesh Jute
Association Abdur Razzak, demanded the government to re-fix weekly
holidays on Saturday and Sunday instead of Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In support of their demand, they said that Saturday and Sunday
are being observed as weekly holidays everywhere of the world.
</P>
<P>
"For running our business smoothly and improving our
communications with outside world, Saturday and Sunday should be
declared holidays," they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
