<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Doubts Palestinian-Israeli Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat's advisor Ahmed Tibi said today a
Palestinian-Israeli summit is still in doubt as there is no
apparent progress from Egypt's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arab radio, he
lauded the Sharm el-Sheikh summit held last Tuesday between
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
But he downplayed the possibility of holding a meeting between
Arafat and Netanyahu, something Mubarak hoped to arrange in the
coming weeks after his three-hour talks with the Israeli leader
last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tibi reaffirmed only a stop to the Israeli settlement can
kickstart the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We will never accept resumption of negotiations with the
Israelis before freezing settlement activities and bringing
confiscation of Palestinian lands to an end," he said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks broke down when Israel began
building Har Homa Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in
March. The Palestinians have made their return to the negotiating
table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu has refused to stop the Har Homa
construction and instead proposed building a neighborhood for
Arabs near the Jewish housing project.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the severity of the two-month-old crisis, clashes
broke out Friday between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the
West Bank town of Bethlehem. Two were wounded when some 500
hundred Palestinians marched to protest the death of a Palestinian
man in Israeli custody.  
</P>
</TEXT>
