<HEADLINE> GCC to Hold Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The six states of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) are planning to hold a new round of
military exercises within the next three or four months to boost
their defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
All the GCC members will begin joint war games in August or
September, local daily Gulf News today quoted a senior Bahraini
defense official as saying, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The manoeuvre follows on the heels of the joint air mock
battles by Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Kuwait and the
United States which began on May 25.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the new GCC joint military exercises
are aimed at ensuring the defense preparedness and boosting
cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
"We are working closely to ensure peace and security in the
region through various ways such as holding joint military
exercises," the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War, the GCC states, namely Bahrain, the
UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar and Oman, have sought ways to
strengthen their self-defense capabilities by purchasing advanced
arms, establishing joint armed forces and holding military
exercises to face claimed threats from Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, the GCC is still heavily reliant on a large foreign
presence, particularly that of the U.S. and its western allies to
protect their security because of limited human resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
