<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: ASEAN FMs Unanimous on ASEAN Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today reached a
unanimous decision on the ASEAN expansion by admitting Cambodia,
Laos and Myanmar into the regional grouping in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The historic and unanimous decision by the ASEAN foreign
ministers at their special meeting held here today is turning into
reality the vision of a united Southeast Asia or ASEAN-10
comprising all the countries in the dynamic region. ASEAN
celebrates its 30th anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, who chaired
the special meeting, told a news conference that "it is a
unanimous decision. There were no reservations on the part of any
ASEAN members."
</P>
<P>
It was in the interest of the region that the three countries
were accepted into the fold, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar will be formally admitted into the
regional grouping at the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) to be
held here in July.
</P>
<P>
Presently, ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore,
the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
All the seven members except Brunei were represented at the
special meeting by their foreign ministers while Brunei was
represented by its Ambassador-at-Large Princess Hajjah Masna.
ASEAN Secretary-General Ajit Singh also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided that Abdullah would visit the three
countries to inform them officially of the decision.
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether ASEAN, by deciding to admit the three
countries in July, wanted to send a signal that it was not being
pressured, Abdullah said ASEAN had no intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
"We signal to nobody. We just make a decision of what is good
for ASEAN and what is good for the region. We have no intention to
pass a message to anybody," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), Abdullah, who is the ASEAN
standing committee chairman, said the three incoming countries
would be given a ten-year period from January 1, 1998 to fulfill
requirements before acceding to it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas broke the
news of the admission date for the incoming ASEAN members to
waiting newsmen outside the meeting room before Abdullah's formal
news conference, saying that it was a good decision.
</P>
<P>
"By having all three enter and becoming part of us, we are
complete now," he said, adding this would place ASEAN in a better
position to contribute to regional peace and stability as well as
a larger East Asia region.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said the ministers
felt that it was better to have the three countries into ASEAN
now.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam said the decision
to accept Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar in July was because of their
readiness and the fact that they have met the requirements.
</P>
<P>
He said the dream and vision of the ASEAN founding fathers will
be realized through the admission of the last three countries.
</P>
<P>
Brunei's Ambassador-at-Large Princess Hajjah Masna said that
the decision was a consensus and Brunei looked forward to the
admission of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
She said the three incoming ASEAN members had met all the
membership requirements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
