<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Singapore to Make Efforts to Mend Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Singapore today
agreed to keep their communication lines open in an effort to mend
bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar, who met his Malaysian
counterpart Abdullah Ahmad Badawi here today, said "both of us
agreed to continue meeting each other and from time to time work
hard to foster better relationship."
</P>
<P>
This is "why we have met today to review our state of bilateral
relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar, who is here to attend the one-day ASEAN foreign
ministers' special meeting, told newsmen after his meeting with
Abdullah that Singapore and Malaysia had been going through a
"very difficult" period and leaders of both countries had spared
no efforts to mend ties as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said on the occasion that he was happy to have met
Jayakumar to discuss ways and means to overcome the "small
problem" which had affected bilateral relations between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Malaysia and Singapore are friends and both have
the responsibility to maintain good relations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, today's ASEAN foreign ministers' special meeting
decided to admit Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos into the regional
grouping in July this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
