<HEADLINE> Largest Inkslab Marks Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The largest and heaviest inkslab in
China has just been built in Dalian, in northeast China's Liaoning
Province, to mark the return of Hong Kong to the Motherland.
</P>
<P>
The inkslab is 6.3 meters long, 2.36 meters wide, and 1.2
meters high, and weighs 28 tons.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding designs on the inkslab are two eight-story
towers and two dragons, signaling the unity of the Chinese nation,
as well as a tortoise turning back its head, which stands for Hong
Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
One hundred scenic spots are featured along the sides of the
inkslab, including the Great Wall and mountains and rivers in
Guilin, and beasts, fishes, birds, and figures which vividly
reflect the traditional Chinese culture and legends.
</P>
<P>
The inkslab is a brainchild of Xing Liangkun, a porcelain
artist in Dalian. The stone to make the inkslab is from the
Taihang Mountains in north China's Hebei Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
