<HEADLINE> Beijing Education Authority Names 1,000 "Smoke-Free" Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- About one third of Beijing's
primary and middle schools have been designated as "Smoke-Free
Schools" because of their successful work to prevent teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
The number of such schools increased to 1,000 from 106 in the
past year with the implementation of a local regulation on banning
smoking in public places, an official of the Beijing Municipal
Education Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
Through various means, the schools have urged students not to
smoke, not to sell or buy cigarettes, to tell their families to
stop smoking or smoke less, and to discourage people from smoking
in public places, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese health experts and officials hold that tight control of
teenage smoking is vital to China's anti-tobacco campaign. As a
nation, China is a big tobacco producer and consumer with some 350
million smokers and more than 400 million passive smokers.
</P>
<P>
Experts warn that without strict measures, there may be 200
million teenage smokers by the year 2000, and 50 million of them
may die from tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Chinese health departments are launching a national
anti-smoking drive today, the 10th World No-Tobacco Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
