<HEADLINE> OAU Ministers Deny U.N. Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Organisation of African Unity (OAU) states yesterday
categorically denied a proposal by the U.N. general assembly to
have two categories of permanent members to the Security Council
-- some with veto powers and others without.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending 66th session of OAU Council of
Ministers meeting here agreed to reccommend to the heads of state
and government meeting next week for the OAU summit to adopt a
Harare declaration which clearly spelt out Africa's position on
the proposed restructuring of the U.N. Security Council, said
chairman of the meeting and Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
The declaration would be a marriage of proposals the heads of
state agreed on in 1994 in Tunis and the position taken by the
African foreign ministers meeting just as that taken at the
Non-Aligned Movement meeting in New Delhi early this year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Africa wants the Security Council expanded to 26 and is
demanding two permanent seats in the council.
</P>
<P>
There was unanimous agreement that the OAU and the U.N. should
help the government of the Democratic Republic of Congo as it
reconstructs its country.
</P>
<P>
On Burundi, the ministers called for intensified negotiations
for peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
