<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Indonesia Sign Pact on Island Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Indonesia have
signed an agreement formally submitting an island dispute to the
International Court of Justice (ICJ) in the Hague, the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here today by Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi and his Indonesian counterpart Ali
Alatas who is here to attend a one-day special meeting of the
ASEAN foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said in a statement that this "represents a very
historic occasion in the bilateral relations between our two
countries" when the two sides agreed to refer to the ICJ their
claims over the islands of Pulau Ligitan and Pulau Sipadan in the
overlapping area of continental shelves that border the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said leaders of both countries have expressed the wish that
this issue should be resolved peacefully through negotiations so
as not to impede the existing "excellent bilateral relations".
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian foreign minister said in a separate statement on
the occasion that "it is to the mutual interest of our two
countries that the case of Pulau Sipadan and Ligitan be settled
peacefully through an adjudication process in the ICJ at the
earliest possible time."
</P>
<P>
The two ministers were of the view that the decision to submit
the case to the ICJ for a final settlement would prevent the issue
from becoming a burden to future generations of both countries
with an unresolved dispute.
</P>
<P>
They said that the two countries would accept the judgment that
will be delivered by the ICJ at the Hague, the Netherlands, as
final and binding.
</P>
<P>
Both of them also hoped that a final and lasting resolution of
the issue would be a major contribution towards the maintenance of
peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Indonesia agreed last October to take the case to
the Hague after years of talks failed to reach a bilateral
solution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
