<HEADLINE> African States to Bust Security Council Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- African countries decided
to bust the U.N. Security Council sanctions imposed on Libya and
have mandated the secretary-general of the Organisation of
African Unity (OAU) to start preparing a plan of action to spare
the Libyan people from further suffering as a result of the
embargo.
</P>
<P>
The 66th session of the OAU Council of Ministers meeting
yesterday recommended that the OAU heads of state and government
adopt sanctions busting only if the Security Council did not
accept one of the proposals adopted jointly by the League of Arab
States and supported by the Non-Aligned Movedment.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said, ''This has become imperative more so as
the sanctions are having an increasing devastating effect on the
people of Libya, as well as on the country's economy.''
</P>
<P>
The ministers strongly deplored the fact that the U.S. and
Britain had shown indifference to the intiatives presented to
them with the views to obtain a just and equitable solution to
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministers unanimously agreed that OAU heads of state and
government should make an appeal to the international community
and the Security Council to envisage as a prelude to the lifting
of the sanctions provisions for exempting from the embargo
flights for humanitarian and religious purposes.
</P>
<P>
Libya has suffered economically losing billions of dollars
because of the sanctions. 
</P>
