<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn's Gold Revaluation Plan Raises Doubt About Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Germany's plan to revalue the
country's central bank's gold reserves has hit unprecedented
repercussions both at home and abroad and raised doubt about the
future of the single European currency only 18 months before its
scheduled launching.
</P>
<P>
Designed as a quick fund-raising measure to ease Germany's debt
burden and to help the nation to qualify for the planned single
currency, the Euro, the plan has been widely criticized as a
trickery which would eventually undermine the Euro.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, gold reserves of the German central
bank, the Bundesbank, have been undervalued.
</P>
<P>
Under the revaluation plan, Bonn wants the Bundesbank to boost
its reserves to 60 percent of market value instead of the current
25 percent, a move which would force the bank to pay more dividend
to the government and thus help bring Germany's public debts under
60 percent of the gross domestic product, a key requirement for
qualification for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Controversies over the plan hit the headlines across Europe
after the Bundesbank issued a strongly-worded statement Wednesday,
saying that the revaluation infringed the central bank's
independence and violated the spirit of the European Union
Maastricht treaty.
</P>
<P>
The move would also risk "a loss in the trust of stability of
the future European currency," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Undaunted by the warning, Bonn still vows to press ahead with
its plan by passing a legislation in parliament to pave the way
for the revaluation.
</P>
<P>
The quarrel with the Bundesbank dramatized Germany's current
financial difficulties against a backdrop of nearly record
unemployment and an expected shortfall of 18 billion mark (about
10.6 billion U.S. dollars) in the budget for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Although it still boasts the most important economy and
strongest currency in Europe, Germany is now in the embarrassing
position of not being able to meet the stringent standards it
insisted that all participants in the Euro meet, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has long opposed any quick-fix accounting solutions to
meet the Euro requirements, aiming most of its attacks at Italy
and France.
</P>
<P>
By announcing the plan to revalue the Bundesbank's reserves,
Germany was losing the authorities to police other EU nations'
fiscal policies in order to safeguard stability of the Euro,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse, the open conflict between the government
and the Bundesbank also threatens to diminish acceptance of the
Euro among the German people.
</P>
<P>
For the Germans, the Bundesbank stands for reasonable banking
policy and therefore is the model for the planned European central
bank. The bank's independence is held by many Germans as their
ultimate defense against the nightmare of inflation.
</P>
<P>
The reason why a majority of German citizens remain mistrustful
of the Euro is that its creation would mean trading their
traditionally hard mark for an unpredictable Euro.
</P>
<P>
If the government fails to summon up enough confidence in the
Euro, it would face a hard test in the next general election
scheduled for autumn next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970531.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Official Criticises Aid Reduction to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An official of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) said on Friday the agency is concerned
with the reduction in aid to Africa, a situation which is
compromising development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
UNDP Director of External Relations Edward Omotoso said despite
convictions by some sections of the international community, Africa
still needs support for its development.
</P>
<P>
''There is a dangerous trend to say that many of the things should
be given to the private sector, then economic growth will be
realised, Africa still needs development aid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Western donors have dictated that the continent should develop its
private sector which has been identified as the engine for growth.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP is allocating a third of its budget into projects
involving good governance.
</P>
<P>
''We want to encourage good governance, democracy, openness,
transparency and improvement of the civil service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable human development through poverty eradication,
economic growth and environmental regeneration are some of the
projects of the UNDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
