<HEADLINE> One Israeli Soldier Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- One Israeli soldier was killed
late Friday in a mortar attack by the pro-Iranian Hezbollah
forces in South Lebanon, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The soldier, whose name was not released for publication,
suffered serious injuries in the attack in the central sector of
the Israeli-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon. He died at
hospital later.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops retaliated by returning fire at Hezbollah
positions, and there was heavy exchange of fire in the area. No
Hezbollah casualties were reported, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah issued a statement claiming responsibility for the
Friday attack, but it strongly denied Israeli reports that two
Hezbollah gunmen were killed Thursday by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident signaled the continuation of recent wave
of fighting in the 1,100-square-kilometer zone, which was set up
by Israel in 1985 to protect its northern border from
cross-border attack by Hezbollah forces.
</P>
<P>
During the past weeks, there has been nearly daily exchange of
fires between Israeli troops and the Hezbollah forces.
</P>
<P>
On May 17, three Israeli soldiers and two Hezbollah gunmen
were killed in an ambush by Hezbollah forces in north of the
security zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that Hezbollah leaders recently had met with
Iran's Ambassador to Lebanon to discuss the victory of moderate
cleric Mohammed Khatami in Iran's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli observers predicted that there would be little
effect of the Iran's elections on its continued support to
Hezbollah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
