<HEADLINE> Israeli Officer Killed in Guerrilla Attack in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- One Israeli officer was killed
Friday night in an attack by guerrillas of the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the Israeli self-proclaimed
"security zone" in south Lebanon, security sources said this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas announced that they launched the attack
at an Israeli foot patrol on the road between the villages of
Markaba and Rob Thalathin, "killing and wounding a number of
Israeli soldiers."
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army spokesman confirmed that one Israeli officer
died from serious wound inflicted in the guerrilla attack Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the Islamic Resistance, the
military wing of Hezbollah, said its fighters used machineguns and
rocket-propelled grenades in the operation.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas launched today another attack on the
Israeli position of Sujoud in the northern sector of the buffer
zone at 5:30 a.m. (0230 GMT), the Shiite militant organization
said in a second statement, noting more Israeli casualties were
caused.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the attack, Israeli artillery fire more
than 30 heavy shells at villages opposite the border strip
without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
However, security sources said that the fightings did not go
beyond daily trades of fire between Lebanese guerrillas and
Israeli occupation forces on the last active battlefront of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Since this year, nine Israeli soldiers have been killed and
more than 40 others wounded in clashes with Hezbollah, which
spearheads a guerrilla warfare in south Lebanon to oust the
Israeli troops out of the Lebanese land.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state established the 1,100-square-kilometer
"security zone" in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect northern
Israel from cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
