<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Committed to Stability, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Zongya)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The 33rd summit of the
Organization of African Unity to be held in Harare on June 2-4
will focus its discussions on political stability and the
pressing task of economic development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that Africa suffers from many ills and
misfortunes, ranging from poverty, underdevelopment to the
tragedies arising from natural and man-made disasters.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been compounded by various conflicts that
have torn apart many of African countries, bleeding African
people and undermining their efforts at socio-economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Conscious of the fact that meaningful development of Africa
will remain elusive as long as instability and insecurity prevail
in the poor continent, the OAU has decided to address the scourge
of conflicts as a priority on its agenda.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the 1990s, the OAU has concentrated its
efforts on promoting peace, security and stability in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
So far, the OAU has been involved directly or indirectly in
peace efforts aimed at resolving conflicts in many African
countries, such as Liberia, Somalia, Sierra Leone, Burundi,
Rwanda and Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Central Organ of the Mechanism for Conflicts
Prevention, Management and Resolution, set up in 1993,
has been playing a major role in these peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The OAU's growing efforts to monitor and mediate disputes are
paying off. In recent years, the OAU's quiet diplomacy has helped
keep democracy on track in Congo and Comoros. It has broken
ground in sending military observers to Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The OAU has also managed to defuse the crisis which emerged in
the Comoros following the mercenary-led coup in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
Most recently, the OAU has tried its best to seek a negotiated
settlement to the Zaire conflict, which started in October last
year.
</P>
<P>
The OAU and the United Nations have jointly proposed a
five-point peace plan on the Zaire crisis and appointed a special
envoy, Mohamed Sahnoun, to mediate between the then Zairean
government of President Mobutu Sese Seko and the rebels led by
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, the OAU central organ held in Lome,
capital of Togo, a special summit on the Zaire crisis, which for
the first time brought a face-to-face meeting between the two
sides of Zaire and opened channels for their direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Though the two sides did not reach consensus at the summit,
the OAU's peace efforts have contributed a lot to avoiding a
bloodbath in Zaire's capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming OAU summit will also discuss the situation in
the Great Lakes region, especially in Zaire, which is now renamed
the Democratic Republic of Congo with Kabila as its president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970531.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Committed to Stability, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Zongya)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Ironically, millions of people in
Africa, one of the potentially richest continents in the world,
are living in the conditions of squalor and abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, economic development and integration of the African
continent also constitute a challenge and priority to the OAU.
</P>
<P>
Just as Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge put it on May
14 this year, "Pan-Africanism has triumphed, we have triumphed on
the political front and now we are on the economic war front."
</P>
<P>
In 1991, leaders of OAU member states held a meeting in Abuja
of Nigeria and adopted a treaty establishing the African Economic
Community.
</P>
<P>
The treaty provides for a framework for the gradual
establishment of the African Economic Community culminating in
the free movement of people and goods and the creation of
continental institutions such as the African Parliament and the
African Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
During the initial stage of implementation of the treaty, the
OAU has laid its emphasis on strengthening the regional economic
communities which constitute the building blocks of the African
Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
Some regional economic groupings like the Southern African
Development Community and the Economic Community of West African
States have already made significant progress.
</P>
<P>
Parallel to the integration efforts, the OAU countries have
been conducting bold economic and structural reforms aimed at
improving the performance and efficiency of the African
economies.
</P>
<P>
As political stability has been gradually consolidated in most
of African states in recent years, their economic performance is
becoming better and better.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest report by the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA), the continent's economy increased by
3.96 percent in 1996, the highest since the start of the current
decade.
</P>
<P>
On the general situation in Africa, there is no doubt that
Africa is moving on the right path, said OAU Secretary General
Salim Ahmed Salim in a statement on the occasion of the 34th
anniversary of the OAU Day which falls on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Though Africa continues to be faced with the scourge of
conflicts, poverty, illiteracy, diseases and a large number of
refugees, Salim stressed that the African people have the capacity,
the will and determination to forge ahead to an era of peace and
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
