<HEADLINE> Thai Police Step up Drug Crackdown in Border Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Thai police in the country's
northernmost province of Chiang Rai, part of the drug-producing
"golden triangle", have stepped up drug trafficking crackdown this
year.
</P>
<P>
To combat the spread of illicit drugs, 24 police checkpoints
have been set up this year to block the transit routes of drugs in
the province.
</P>
<P>
In addition, on-line computerized systems have also been
installed in every police station to provide information about
identities of suspected drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
As a result, in the first five months this year, police
arrested 326 drug suspects in districts along the border and
confiscated more than 600,000 amphetamine tablets, as compared
with the 413 arrests and 1.05 million tablets for the whole of
1996, according to local police.
</P>
<P>
Amphetamine production plants are mostly located along the
Thai-Myanmar and Thai-Laotian border areas, known as the "golden
triangle".
</P>
<P>
Police Maj.-Gen. Sunthorn Bunchiang, commander of Chiang Rai
Police, said rooting out drugs was not easy, as very often only
the local drivers of pick-up trucks and vans which were carrying
drugs were arrested. Major suppliers who hired the drivers are
hard to get.
</P>
<P>
Amphetamine tablets are in particular easy to be smuggled into
Thailand from Myanmar as the border river is very shallow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
