<HEADLINE> Bosnian Presidency Harshly Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINTRA, Portugal, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Peace
Implementation Council (PIC) harshly criticized Bosnia's
three-person presidency here today, and called on it to fully
implement the Dayton Peace Accords.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that proper implementation was regarded as one
of the important conditions for getting international aid.
</P>
<P>
The help Bosnia will receive from the international community
will be dependent on the commitment it demonstrates to the peace
agreement, representatives attending PIC organized meeting said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting cited the failure to capture war criminals and help
refugees return to their homes, as among the tripartite's failures
to meet the Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
The PIC has set specific target dates by which the Bosnians
will have to meet concrete objectives or face penalties.
</P>
<P>
The PIC announced that a donors' conference will be held on
June 24 in Brussels in hopes of raising l.4 billion U.S. dollars
for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also appointed Carlos Westendorp, Spain's
ambassador to the United Nations, as top civilian envoy in Bosnia
to replace former Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt, who will
return to Sweden next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
