<HEADLINE>   Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican footwear industry exported 8,000
pairs of shoes in the first three months of this year, of which 70
percent was sold to the United States. This figure exceeded plans.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay foreign currency earned by tourism
amounted to 423.5 million U.S. dollars during the first quarter of
this year, a 25.5 percent increase over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Tourism Ministry shows that 997,556 people
visited the country, a 17.5 percent rise over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Investments of 1.1 billion dollars will go into
the mining industry in the next two years in the province of
Catamarca.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to build the main installations of the
mine in Catamarca, and to operate a port owned by the company.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Latin American banana producing countries
exported bananas worth 1.28 billion dollars last year, Euclides
Diaz, secretary of the Banana Exporting Countries Association
(UPEB), said.
</P>
<P>
Diaz said the figure excluded Mexico's exports. The UPEB member
countries will make an assessment of progress in the agreements
signed with the Interamerican Institute for Cooperation in
Agriculture (IICA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
