<HEADLINE> Indian PM: Nepal, Bhutan Should Talk Refugee Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral has reiterated his country's position that the Bhutanese
refugee problem in Nepal could only be sorted out bilaterally, the
local press here said today.
</P>
<P>
Gujral, while meeting with a visiting Nepali journalists
delegation in New Delhi Friday, said that both Nepal and Bhutan
are sovereign nations and they should solve the refugee problem
bilaterally.
</P>
<P>
"Third party intervention in any other's affairs is dangerous,"
the Indian prime minister reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government has always refused Nepal's demand for its
mediation for the solution of the lingering Bhutanese refugee
problem in Nepal. India handles foreign and defense affairs for
Bhutan under a bilateral treaty.
</P>
<P>
Around 100,000 Bhutanese, mostly of Nepalese origin, have been
living in eight refugee camps in eastern Nepal since 1990 when
they fled to Nepal via Indian territory forcibly under Bhutanese
authorities' ethnic cleansing policy, Nepali officials said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, seven rounds of bilateral talks at the ministerial
level between the two Himalayan nations made no progress in the
settlement of the controversial issue as Bhutan maintained that
many of the refugees were not genuine Bhutanese citizens and
refused their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Gujral is expected to arrive here next
Thursday on a three-day goodwill visit to Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
