<HEADLINE> Brazil, Argentina to Build Environmental Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and Argentina will
start the construction next year of a teledetection satellite for
the surveillance of the environment, including agriculture and
water systems, of South America.
</P>
<P>
The details of the project have been discussed in Brazil by
Brazilian Minister of Science and Technology Israel Vargas, and
his Argentine counterpart Juan Carlos del Bello, an informed
source was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the satellite will cost 16 million
U.S. dollars, to be contributed by both countries, which will also
share technical work.
</P>
<P>
The date for the launching has not been determined, but it
could begin operating in six or seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
