<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polling at 67 Stations in Indonesia to Be Repeated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An election supervisory committee
official in East Java, Indonesia, said voting at 67 polling
stations in Sampang on the Island of Madura, would be repeated,
official Antara News agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The repeat voting will be done on June 4 or 5 as vote counting
has to be completed by June 6, Secretary of the East Java Election
Supervisory Committee Soerjadi Setiawan said Friday in Suarabaya,
the second largest city in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The repetition of the voting is done following riots in Sampang
 Thursday when the general election was held across the country.
The riots caused several ballot boxes missing from the Dedungdung
sub-district before the votes were counted.
</P>
<P>
He said reserved ballot boxes totaling some 3,000 in East Java
would be used for the repeat voting.
</P>
<P>
Riots broke out in several East Java cities after Thursday's
preliminary election results gave the ruling Golkar group an
overwhelming lead.
</P>
<P>
The worst incident occurred at 16:00 local time Thursday and
lasted until 18:00 on Madura Island, located off the north coast
of East Java, Antara said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of angry residents in the capital of Sampang went on
the rampage, burning down two government offices, the local police
headquarters, the regional Golkar office, banks and shops, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The trouble started when locals demanded a recount after being
told of Golkar's huge lead over the United Development Party
(PPP).
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported in the incident, but police
admitted that scores were injured. Seven of them suffered shot
wounds.
</P>
<P>
Police said 24 people have been arrested for their alleged
involvement in the violence and investigation is still under way.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisional results, Golkar had won 74.16
percent of the votes counted up to 11:19 p.m. Friday, the PPP
gained 22.84 percent and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI)
clinched 3 percent of the 107,613,316 votes counted.
</P>
<P>
A total of 124,741,987 people were eligible to vote in
Thursday's election to elect 425 members of the 500-seat House of
Representatives, as well as members of provincial and
district/municipal councils.
</P>
<P>
With the ballots counted by Friday, Golkar's position to clinch
a landslide victory will not be affected by the final result of
the counting which will be released later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
