<HEADLINE> Canadians View Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- A two-week-long Hong Kong
Photography Exhibition opened in the regional municipality of
Ottawa-Carleton here today.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, sponsored by the Chinese Embassy, displays 99
pictures that best reflect the past and the status of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will help Canadians, especially Chinese
Canadians here, to better understand Hong Kong, which will return
to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Canada Zha Peixin told the opening
ceremony that Hong Kong's return to the motherland marks a major
historic event, which will wipe out a national disgrace in the
past century.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will steadfastly uphold the "one
country, two systems" policy and maintain the long-term prosperity
and stability of Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's prosperity and stability are in the interests of
both the Chinese people and the peoples of Canada and other
countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Brian MaGarry, councillor of the municipality, said it will be
a "fascinating experience to observe" Hong Kong return to China.
</P>
<P>
He said China's policy of "one country, two systems" will
contribute to Hong Kong's prosperity and to China's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is scheduled to move on to Canada's second
largest city of Montreal in late June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
