<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM to Visit Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
will fly to Tirana on Sunday for a round of political talks with
Albanian leaders and a visit to the Italian military headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Italian officials here said that Prodi will meet Albanian
President Sali Berisha and Prime Minister Bashkim Fino, and
General Luciano Forlani, who commands the Italian-led
multinational protection force (MPF) in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, the major driving force of the MPF, decided to visit
Albania following a series of violent incidents in the troubled
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night the arrival of an Italian helicopter, which
came to evacuate a 14-year-old girl wounded in the head when she
and her brother were playing with a pistol, in the rebel-held
southern port of Vlore, provoked a massive outburst of automatic
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
But Vlore Salvation Committee deputy leader Dashmir Beja denied
today that the shooting was aimed at the Italian troops. He said
many people thought it was Berisha's forces trying to storm the
port, because it was the first time that a helicopter had arrived
at night.
</P>
<P>
In daytime on Thursday, armed men held up a group of Italian
election monitors trying to travel from Tirana to the town of
Gjirokaster to advise on election procedures. The monitors were
sent back at a road block.
</P>
<P>
General elections are due on June 29 in Albania, which was
gripped by violence following the failure of investment schemes in
March. The MPF has the role of trying to create a relatively
peaceful atmosphere for the poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
