<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Ruling Party Wins 74 Percent of Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Provisional results of vote
counting by the Indonesian Election Committee (PPI) up to 11:19
p.m. Friday indicated that the ruling party Golkar had won 74.16
percent of the votes counted.
</P>
<P>
The United Development Party (PPP) gained 22.84 percent and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) clinched 3 percent of the
107,613,316 votes counted.
</P>
<P>
The PPI announced that the PPP won 24.576 million votes, Golkar
79.804 million votes and the PDI 3.23 million votes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 124,740,987 people were eligible to vote in
Thursday's election to elect 425 members of the 500-seat House of
Representatives, as well as members of provincial and
district/municipal councils.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 75 seats of the House are reserved for the armed
forces whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
With the ballots counted by Friday night, Golkar's position to
clinch a landslide victory will not be affected by the final
result of the counting.
</P>
<P>
Golkar won 68 percent of the votes in the 1992 election and has
been aiming for a 70.02 percent win this year. The PPP won 17
percent of the votes in 1992 and the PDI 15 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
