<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Target Rural Health Care in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan will further expand
co-operation on projects which combine rural family planning with
mother and child health care, parasite control and community
development.
</P>
<P>
Chinese State Councillor Peng Peiyun yesterday expressed her
thanks to the Japanese Organization for International Co-operation
in Family Planning (JOICFP) which has supported Chinese family
planning work since 1984, and hoped this friendship and
co-operation will be developed further in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Peng, who is also minister in charge of the State Family
Planning Commission (SFPC), made the remarks yesterday afternoon
during her meeting with JOICFP leaders and experts at the
Diaoyutai State Guest House in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
JOICFP President Sawaki Masao also expressed readiness to
continue and expand co-operation with the Chinese Government and
non-governmental organizations in family planning.
</P>
<P>
JOICFP has consistently attached great significance to
Sino-Japanese co-operation in population, family planning and
health care, said the JOICFP leader, adding his organization will
contribute more for such collaborations.
</P>
<P>
China started its first JOICFP-supported program in 1984. So
far, more than two million rural residents in 26 counties of 22
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have been
involved, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Chinese technicians are being specially trained in
implementation methods. Special offices have been established in
each of the pilot counties and townships to supervise the work.
</P>
<P>
The so-called integrated projects helped mobilize the community
to improve environmental sanitation and establish safe drinking
water sources.
</P>
<P>
It also trained farmers in money-making activities such as
animal raising and vegetable growing. As a result, living
standards improved, the rates of parasitic infection declined and
the birth rate dropped in integrated project pilot areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
