<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Territorial Claim Over Ukraine: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 30, (Xinhua) -- "It is most important that we have no
territorial claim over Ukraine," visiting Russian President Boris
Yeltsin said here today when starting his two-day visit to Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is to sign a treaty of friendship, cooperation and
partnership with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He was welcomed by a salvo of 21 guns, and said he had arrived
in Kiev to sign the political treaty with equality and brotherhood
in mind.
</P>
<P>
The basic principle of the treaty, which is to be signed on
Saturday, is mutual respect to each other's territorial integrity,
and the inviolability of their borders. Initialed two years ago,
the treaty will lay a political foundation for the development of
bilateral relations between Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin added that he came to Kiev with hope and optimism,
believing the treaty would solve all problems between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after their talks, Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma said: "Yeltsin's visit is of great importance. The
treaty to be signed tomorrow will be an historic event." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
