<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Celebrates Victorious Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 30 (Xinhua) -- China celebrated a
victorious day on Friday when it monopolizes all the women's
singles semi-final berths at the world badminton championships.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Open champion Gong Zhichao beat former world champion
and fifth seed Susi Susanti of Indonesia 11-5, 11-2 in just 24
minutes while world junior champion Wang Chen had an equally easy
11-6, 11-4 win over third-seeded Mia Audina, also from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"I am older than my opponent and I am now married," said
Susanti after her second loss in two months to Gong since All
England Open this March.
</P>
<P>
"She will follow my steps to the titles," she said of the
rising star.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals, Gong will face 1995 world championship
silver medalist Han Jingna, who won against Zhang Ning 11-8, 11-7
in the quarter-finals while Wang is to face defending champion Ye
Zhaoying.
</P>
<P>
Three of the women's doubles semi-final slots have also been
occupied by the Chinese shuttlers.
</P>
<P>
Top seed and Olympic champions Ge Fei and Gu Jun swept past
sixth-seeded Rikke Olsen and Helene Kirkegaard of Denmark 15-2,
15-8 in 25 minutes to set up a semi-final clash against
compatriots Qian Hong and Liu Lu, who defeated Indonesia's Denyana
Lomban and Indarti Isoliana 15-10, 15-6.
</P>
<P>
All England runners-up Eliza and Rosiana Zelin rolled over
Malaysia's unseeded pair Chor Hooi Yee and Lim Pek Siah to meet
Chinese duo Tang Yongshu and Qin Yiyuan, who scored a come-from
behind win over European champions Marlene Thomsen and Lisbet
Stuer-Lauridsen of Denmark 7-15, 15-8, 15-1.
</P>
<P>
In men's singles, in which China suffered the withdrawl of top
seed Dong Jiong, the country still has world number three Sun Jun
go through to the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jun defeated Peter Gade Christensen of Denmark to face
Denmark's Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen, who was
extended by Joko Suprianto to three games in a quarter-final.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Heryanto Arbi of Indonesia rallied from one
game down to edge another Dane Thomas Stuer-Lauridsen to take on
Peter Rasmussen, also from Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen survived second game thrill to beat Park Sung Woo of
South Korea 15-2 and 18-17, revenging his loss to Park in a
Sudirman Cup match last week.
</P>
<P>
In men's doubles semi-finals, Yap Kim Hock and Cheah Soon Kit
of Malaysia will face Indonesia's Olympic gold medalists Rexy
Mainaky and Ricky Subagja while another Indonesian pair Budiarto
Sigit and Candra Wijaya will face Lee Dong Soo and Yoo Yong Sung,
South Korea's only semi-finalists in all five events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
