<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Sports Without Smoke" Campaign Launched in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The "Sports Without Smoke"
campaign was launched today in Uruguay on occasion of the World
Day Without Smoking.
</P>
<P>
The campaign exhorts people who practice sports to abandon the
tobacco habit, to give an example to the rest of the population.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was started by the Health Ministry, the
Panamerican Health Organization (OPS), and the Uruguayan
Anti-Smoking Commission (CATU), which will offer a free treatment
"to the most outstanding Uruguayan soccer players" who want to
abandon the habit.
</P>
<P>
A similar campaign was started a month ago when the same
organizations opened a registry for newsmen who wanted to take the
treatment.
</P>
<P>
OPS spokesman Dr. Ricardo Benedetti said "we cannot offer the
treatment free to all smokers because it would be very costly,"
but he explained that "we chose newsmen and now soccer players
because we thought they have to give the example to society."
</P>
<P>
Sports medicine specialist Maria Emilia Alvarez said that "the
modern concept of health is not only the psyco-physical and social
wellbeing, but also the full development of human potential, and
to achieve that health and sports go hand in hand."
</P>
<P>
Almost 35 percent of the Uruguayan population smoke, and from
this percentage 45 percent are women, almost twice the habitual
average of women who smoke in Western countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
