<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Stabilized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 30 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rallied back today
from an early plunge triggered by news that computer chip giant
Intel expects to report disappointing profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average recovered from an early
88-point deficit, rising less than a point to about 7,331.04,
trimming the week's loss to 14.87.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by more than a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume jumped to 533.42 million
shares from 460.48 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also rebounded from the early slide, which saw
the Nasdaq composite index tumble nearly 50 points, or about 3.5
percent, after a sharp selloff in Intel's shares.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.20 to 848.28; and
the NYSE composite index rose 2.92 to 441.78, beating Tuesday's
record close.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell just 2.78 to 1,400.32.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 list of smaller companies rose 2.32 to 380.75,
closing at a record high for the sixth straight session. The
American Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated by
smaller companies, rose 2.26 to 605.38.
</P>
<P>
Bonds rose today after the Commerce Department reported that
sales of new single-family homes fell 7.7 percent in April, the
sharpest decline in six months and down from an 11-year high in
March.
</P>
<P>
But in a separate report, the Commerce Department reported that
the nation's economic growth surged at a 5.8 percent annual rate
during the first three months of this year, the best in a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
