<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US-New Zealand Conclude Open-Skies Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States and New
Zealand have reached an "open skies" agreement permitting
unrestricted airline operation between the countries, the U.S.
Transportation Department announced today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the airlines of the two countries have the
right to operate between and beyond the countries, eliminating
restrictions on how often carriers can fly, their prices and the
types of planes they can use.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has been actively negotiating for such
agreements with other countries and regions. In Asia, similar
deals have been signed with China's Taiwan, Singapore and Brunei.
Such negotiations are under way with Malaysia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The country also has open-skies accords with 12 countries in
Europe and six in Central America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
