<DOCNO> XIE19970531.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says Russia Won't Take Measures Against NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States believes that
Russia will not take any "countermeasures" against the expansion
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), a senior U.S.
defense official told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at the Pentagon, Assistant
Secretary of Defense Franklin D. Kramer said that he anticipated
the U.S.-Russian relations "will be good" despite differences
between them on NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"There were discussions by various individuals in Russia about
the motions of countermeasures, but the government has never
indicated to do that," Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
"And the reality is that what the Russian government has done
is that it signed the Founding Act," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO and Russia signed the document in Paris
earlier this week for future cooperation. But Moscow is still
strongly opposed to the alliance's enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"We don't anticipate any `countermeasures' (from Russia),"
Kramer noted. "What we do anticipate is to work closely with the
Russians on matters of mutual security."
</P>
<P>
He also indicated that neither NATO nor the U.S. sees Russia as
a potential enemy. Moscow insisted that NATO's enlargement will
bring the alliance's front-line to its doorstep, threatening its
national security.
</P>
<P>
"NATO enlargement is a part of an overall process of a
transformation of European security in the post-Cold War period,"
Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the enlargement, the process also includes issues like
the new Founding Act, NATO's own internal transformation and the
Partnership for Peace program involving 27 countries, Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
"Fundamental reasons for all these activities are to enhance,
reserve the stability and security in Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders will meet in July in Madrid to choose which
countries should be accepted in the first wave of expansion.
Kramer noted that the difficulty that is facing the alliance is to
choose whom.
</P>
<P>
Though the U.S. has not publicly stated which countries should
join first, U.S. officials said that the Clinton administration
favors a smaller group of countries, like Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
France and other southern European NATO members have indicated
that they would like to see Romania and Slovenia to be in the
first wave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
