<HEADLINE> US Dollar Mostly Up on European Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar overcame weakness
from an early stock-market selloff today, rising against most
European currencies.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled in New York at its highest weekly closing
level in four weeks against the mark and highest weekly close in
three weeks against the yen.
</P>
<P>
In New York, it settled at 1.7063 marks, up from 1.6966 marks
Thursday. Against the yen, the dollar ended slightly lower at
116.22 yen, down from 116.28 yen Thursday. The pound cost 1.6410
U.S. dollars, up from 1.6404 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traders said news from the Commerce Department that the economy
grew at a 5.8 percent rate in the first quarter of the year,
higher than expectation, suggesting that interest rates in the
United States could rise. Higher rates would strengthen dollar.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late Thursday:
1.4129 Swiss francs, up from 1.4103; 5.7595 French francs, up from
5.7310; 1,692.50 Italian lire, up from 1,679.50; 1.3770 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.3803. 
</P>
</TEXT>
